,"Scotland":"Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1340–":"1340–Overleden","1340–Female":"1340–Overleden","1370–Female":"1370–Overleden","1340–Male":"1340–Overleden","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Scotland":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1340–":"1340–Deceased","1340–Female":"1340–Deceased","1370–Female":"1370–Deceased","1340–Male":"1340–Deceased","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stewart","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire) and English: originally an occupational name for an administrative official of an estate, from Middle English <i>stiward</i>, Old English <i>stigweard</i>, <i>stīweard</i>, a compound of <i>stig</i> ‘house(hold)’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guardian’. In the Anglo-Saxon period this title was used of an officer controlling the domestic affairs of a household, especially of the royal household; after the Norman Conquest it was also used more widely as the native equivalent of <b>Seneschal</b>, for the steward of a manor or manager of an estate. In Scotland the term was also used of a magistrate originally appointed by the king to administer crown lands, forming a stewartry.","History: Stuart or Stewart is the surname of one of the great families of Scotland, the royal family of Scotland from the 14th century, and of England from 1603, when James VI of Scotland acceded to the English throne as James I. There were many minor branches of the family left in Britain after the flight of James II in 1688, but not every bearer of the surname can claim relationship with the royal house, even in Scotland. Every great house in medieval England and Scotland had its steward, and in many cases the office gave rise to a hereditary surname. The fall of the house of Stuart in Britain, conversely, led to the establishment of several highly placed branches bearing this surname in continental Europe, which are in most cases related to the old Scottish royal family."],"variants":[{"name":"Stuart","meanings":["Scottish (Aberdeenshire and Banffshire): variant of   Stewart  . This French form of the name, there being no W in the French language, was adopted by Mary, Queen of Scots, on her return to Scotland in 1561 and has since come to be more popular among royalists than the earlier spellings.","History: Stuart or Stewart is the surname of one of the great families of Scotland (see note at   Stewart  )."]},{"name":"Stewardson","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Westmorland): patronymic from Middle English <i>stiward</i> ‘steward’ (see   Stewart  ) + <i>-son</i> ‘son of the steward’."]},{"name":"Steward","meanings":["English (London and East Anglia): variant of   Stewart  ."]},{"name":"Steuart","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Stewart  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Stewart was born in 1340, in Scotland, United Kingdom. He married Janet Campbell. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1340–":"1340–Surnud","1340–Female":"1340–Surnud","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1340–":"1340–Kuollut","1340–Female":"1340–Kuollut","1370–Female":"1370–Kuollut","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1340–":"1340–Décédé","1340–Female":"1340–Décédée","1370–Female":"1370–Décédée","1340–Male":"1340–Décédé","1340":"1340","1370":"1370","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Scotland":"Écosse, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"John Stewart est né en 1340, à Écosse, Roya